tspan.tspan: Using Machine Learning and One-Hot Encoding to determine rating for
Boardgames
Maximo Rainwater
Francis Marion University, Mathematics Department
Background
• Machine Learning is the study of algorithms that allow a computer to
make predictions without being expicitly being programmed to know what
decisions make the best predictions
• The predictions are based on sample data given to a neural
network
This scatter plot depicts data points based on two input parameters (number of
misspelled words and number of images), with a decision boundary separating
the space it divides into "yes" and "no"
Descision Quesiton
•"Is this email spam?", is a decision question because it can be
answered with a "yes or "no
• Input parameters correlating with what is considered spam includes
the length of the message, number of images, instances of the word
“yes?”, etc
• Input parameters should be quantifiable
• Confidence is then calculated using the Sigmoid Function which is
then used to calculate Loss using the Cross-entropy Cost Function
One-Hot Encoding
• This method was choosen to be applied to Boardgame reviews
from Boardgame Geek's website
• One-Hot Encoding is the method of indicating a legal combination
of values with a single 1 bit and all others low, 0
Example of One-Hot Encoding
• To start the process of One-Hot Encoding (OHE), the computer
must know what values are legal
A "dictionary" of legal words is given to the OHE along with the
data that
the user wants to be encoded.
The "dictionary" and data are both multidimensional vectors
• The encoder then outputs a binary vector based on the comparison
between the "dictionary" and the dataset (1 for what it is, 0 for what it
isn't).
• These vectors can then be added and be used to determine what
words a sentence has
Description of Methods
• First, a dictionary had to be made for the One Hot Encoder to compare the
words that it's given from the reviews
• A database of 333,333 common English words was used as the dictionary
• A compilation of boardgame reviews that contained ratings and comments
was used as the dataset
• All the punctuation was striped from the reviews
• The encoder is used to turn the words into a vector space of ones and
zeros. Any unknowns are ignored
• In Python, Keras is then used to read the data and construct the network
that uses Stochastic Gradient Descent to optimize the loss function
